<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Abdomen</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
Abdominal tergites I-VII with reticulations consisting of small triangles arranged in polygons (Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 8" captionStartId="F8" captionText="Figure 8. Aspidophorodon reticulatum Qiao &amp; Xu, sp. nov. Apterous viviparous female A dorsal view of head B antenna C ultimate rostral segment D reticulations formed by strings of small triangles arranged in polygons on abdominal tergites E siphunculus F cauda G anal plate H genital plate. Scale bars: 0.10 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1106.77912.figure8" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/702343" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">8D</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 9" captionStartId="F9" captionText="Figure 9. Aspidophorodon reticulatum Qiao &amp; Xu, sp. nov. Apterous viviparous female A dorsal view of body B dorsal view of head C antenna D ultimate rostral segment E hind tibia and tarsi F reticulations formed by strings of small triangles arranged in polygons on abdominal tergites G siphunculus H cauda I anal plate J genital plate. Scale bars: 0.10 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1106.77912.figure9" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/702344" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">9F</figureCitation>
). Dorsal setae of abdomen sparse, short, pointed or slightly blunt, with small setal tubercles; ventral setae short and pointed. Abdominal tergites I-III each with one pair of spinal, pleural and marginal setae; tergites IV-VII each with one pair of spinal and one pair of marginal setae; tergites VIII with one pair of spinal setae. Spiracles reniform and open, spiracular plates slightly swollen. SIPH spoon-shaped, smooth, broad at base, thin at middle, swollen distally, obliquely truncated at tip, without flange (Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 8" captionStartId="F8" captionText="Figure 8. Aspidophorodon reticulatum Qiao &amp; Xu, sp. nov. Apterous viviparous female A dorsal view of head B antenna C ultimate rostral segment D reticulations formed by strings of small triangles arranged in polygons on abdominal tergites E siphunculus F cauda G anal plate H genital plate. Scale bars: 0.10 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1106.77912.figure8" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/702343" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">8E</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 9" captionStartId="F9" captionText="Figure 9. Aspidophorodon reticulatum Qiao &amp; Xu, sp. nov. Apterous viviparous female A dorsal view of body B dorsal view of head C antenna D ultimate rostral segment E hind tibia and tarsi F reticulations formed by strings of small triangles arranged in polygons on abdominal tergites G siphunculus H cauda I anal plate J genital plate. Scale bars: 0.10 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1106.77912.figure9" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/702344" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">9G</figureCitation>
). Cauda elongate conical, slightly constricted at middle, with spinulose imbrications and four setae (Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 8" captionStartId="F8" captionText="Figure 8. Aspidophorodon reticulatum Qiao &amp; Xu, sp. nov. Apterous viviparous female A dorsal view of head B antenna C ultimate rostral segment D reticulations formed by strings of small triangles arranged in polygons on abdominal tergites E siphunculus F cauda G anal plate H genital plate. Scale bars: 0.10 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1106.77912.figure8" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/702343" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">8F</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 9" captionStartId="F9" captionText="Figure 9. Aspidophorodon reticulatum Qiao &amp; Xu, sp. nov. Apterous viviparous female A dorsal view of body B dorsal view of head C antenna D ultimate rostral segment E hind tibia and tarsi F reticulations formed by strings of small triangles arranged in polygons on abdominal tergites G siphunculus H cauda I anal plate J genital plate. Scale bars: 0.10 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1106.77912.figure9" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/702344" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">9H</figureCitation>
). Anal plate semicircular, spinulose (Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 8" captionStartId="F8" captionText="Figure 8. Aspidophorodon reticulatum Qiao &amp; Xu, sp. nov. Apterous viviparous female A dorsal view of head B antenna C ultimate rostral segment D reticulations formed by strings of small triangles arranged in polygons on abdominal tergites E siphunculus F cauda G anal plate H genital plate. Scale bars: 0.10 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1106.77912.figure8" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/702343" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">8G</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 9" captionStartId="F9" captionText="Figure 9. Aspidophorodon reticulatum Qiao &amp; Xu, sp. nov. Apterous viviparous female A dorsal view of body B dorsal view of head C antenna D ultimate rostral segment E hind tibia and tarsi F reticulations formed by strings of small triangles arranged in polygons on abdominal tergites G siphunculus H cauda I anal plate J genital plate. Scale bars: 0.10 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1106.77912.figure9" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/702344" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">9I</figureCitation>
), with 15-16 setae. Genital plate transversely oval, with sparse spinules in transverse rows (Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 8" captionStartId="F8" captionText="Figure 8. Aspidophorodon reticulatum Qiao &amp; Xu, sp. nov. Apterous viviparous female A dorsal view of head B antenna C ultimate rostral segment D reticulations formed by strings of small triangles arranged in polygons on abdominal tergites E siphunculus F cauda G anal plate H genital plate. Scale bars: 0.10 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1106.77912.figure8" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/702343" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">8H</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 9" captionStartId="F9" captionText="Figure 9. Aspidophorodon reticulatum Qiao &amp; Xu, sp. nov. Apterous viviparous female A dorsal view of body B dorsal view of head C antenna D ultimate rostral segment E hind tibia and tarsi F reticulations formed by strings of small triangles arranged in polygons on abdominal tergites G siphunculus H cauda I anal plate J genital plate. Scale bars: 0.10 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1106.77912.figure9" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/702344" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">9J</figureCitation>
), with three or four anterior setae and four setae along the posterior margin.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="etymology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
The species is named for the reticulations apparent on the dorsum of the body, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">reticulatum</emphasis>
being the neuter form of the adjective.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="taxonomic notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Taxonomic notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
The new species resembles 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. harvense" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="harvense">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">A. harvense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Verma but differs from it as follows: antennal tubercles each with a cylindrical process at inner apex, 0.051-0.056mm, 1.82-2.04 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
as long as its width (the latter: antennal tubercles each with a long finger-shaped process at inner apex, 0.110-0.120mm, 2.40-2.50 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
as long as the basal width); dorsum of body with reticulations consist of small triangles arranged in polygons (the latter: dorsum of body with oval and irregular polygonal reticulations); URS 2.70-2.72 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
as long as the basal width, 1.51-1.61 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
as long as 2HT (the latter: URS 1.39-1.63 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
as long as the basal width, 0.69-0.81 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
as long as 2HT).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
